org.apache.uima.analysis_component.AnalysisComponent
public class TagenAE
extends org.apache.uima.analysis_component.JCasAnnotator_ImplBase

This AE encapsulates TagEN, a Named Entities Recognizer (with default configs for French and English). TagEN 2.0 script is called using an ExternalProgram object, and TagEN output is processed using the fr.lipn.uima.util.align package (to recover NEs positions).
Errors are carefully processed, though bugs are always possible (sic!): detailed UIMA exceptions are thrown whenever possible, even when the underlying TagEN process fails (in this case stderr is copied in the exception message).
A time out option is provided, in order to kill the underlying process after a certain amount of time. Of course it should be used with care, since the time needed to process a document depends on a lot of parameters (set to 0 by default, meaning no limit).
Temporary files/directory are created "in the safer way", using Java specs mechanism to manage location and filenames. TagEN 2.0 is also safe about temporary files, therefore no conflict should arise. An option is also provided to force temporary data location. Finally a debug option is provided, which is also transmitted to TagEN, and permits to keep temporary files. It can be used to observe the intermediate steps of the process. The "config" option is transmitted "as is" to TagEN, thus no initialization exception can be raised if this parameter is erroneous. All other parameters are checked (file/directory names).
Information: currently this AE requires that the text does not contain any "<" character, because it is the opening tag mark. ">" are allowed.

Author:
moreau

DEFAULT_TAGEN_ENCODING

public static final java.lang.String DEFAULT_TAGEN_ENCODING
TagEN encoding (UTF-16 Little Endian with BOM). Information about encoding: TagEN relies on Unitex, which requires Unicode UTF-16 Little Endian encoding, WITH a mandatory Byte Order Mark (BOM)... But this very precise requirement is quite unusual for the current Java Specs: Java "New I/O" package (java.nio) is not even able to write such encoding (though it is able to read it). However the "old" java.io and java.lang packages can handle this encoding, using the canonical name UnicodeLittle (which will write a BOM, contrary to UTF16-LE).
Notice that the "iconv" utility seems to always write a BOM when using UTF-16 (I did not check precisely).

Related links:
  • about Unicode standards and Byte Order Mark:
  • http://unicode.org/faq/utf_bom.html
  • http://unicode.org/faq/utf_bom.html#BOM
  • about Java Spec charset encodings:
  • http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/guide/intl/encoding.doc.html
  • http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5.0/docs/api/java/nio/charset/Charset.html
